<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[166,794,1013,1304]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[166,283,1013,1037]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Moderately sized (length 
<quantity box="[606,679,1014,1038]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
), metallic purplish blue flies, with the occiput well-developed dorsally in females, and ocelli in the form of an equilateral triangle. Regarding the Australian fauna, it is most similar to 
<emphasis box="[192,334,1131,1155]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1855" box="[192,330,1131,1155]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Microchrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Microchrysa</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but can be distinguished by the: larger size; head dorsoventrally compressed in anterior view, about 0.6 times as high as wide; lower frons with a distinct triangular callus diverging ventrally towards base of antennae; basal complex of antennal flagellum somewhat large; and more strongly developed veins 
<emphasis box="[440,470,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">
M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[462,470,1290,1304]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[483,514,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">
M 
<subScript attach="right" box="[506,514,1290,1304]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">3</subScript>
</emphasis>
, and 
<emphasis box="[572,603,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">
M 
<subScript attach="right" box="[595,603,1290,1304]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">4</subScript>
</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
